Read gas dataset.

data("gas")
gas.ts <- gas
View(gas.ts)

Check the dataset is time series.

class(gas.ts)
## [1] "ts"
str(gas.ts)
##  Time-Series [1:476] from 1956 to 1996: 1709 1646 1794 1878 2173 ...

The input dataset gas is in time series format. There are 476 observations from 1956 to 1996.

Check the start, end and frequency of data and periodicity of dataset.

start(gas.ts)
## [1] 1956    1
end(gas.ts)
## [1] 1995    8
frequency(gas.ts)
## [1] 12
#39 years 8 months ie. 468+8 =476 observations , 
#each observation is for month starting from jan 1956 till aug 1995

Check the periodicity of data.

periodicity(gas.ts)
## Monthly periodicity from Jan 1956 to Aug 1995

The dataset has Monthly periodicity. It has 476 observations. Each observation is for month starting from Jan 1956 till Aug 1995(39 years 8 months i.e.468+8 = 476 months)

Plot the dataset.

plot(gas,ylab="Gas",pch=20)

Seasonality is observed throughout the period. From 1970 onwards there is an upward trend along with seasonality.

Draw trend line to see overall trend.

plot(gas,ylab="Gas",pch=20)
abline(reg = lm(gas~time(gas.ts)))

Overall upward trend is observed.

Decompose the time series and plot the decomposed series. Plot the components as well.

gas.decompM <- decompose(gas.ts,type = "multiplicative")
plot(gas.decompM,ylab="Decomposed Time Series",pch=20)

Observed values have both trend and seasonality.

Check the seasonal component of decomposed time series and plot it.

Seasonality is clearly visible in the gas time series from above plot.

Check box plot and season plot across months to get us a sense on seasonal effect.

boxplot(gas.ts~cycle(gas.ts))

seasonplot(gas.ts)

By above plots we can understand that gas sales gradually increase till July and then it gradually decreases. The month pf July has highest sale every year.

Time series Stationarity

Check the stationarity of time series using ADF test.

Null Hypothesis(H0): The series has a unit root. That means the time series is non-stationary. Alternate Hypothesis(H1): The series does not have a unit root. That means the time series is stationary.

adf.test(gas.ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  gas.ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.7131, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.2764
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

p-value = 0.2764 > 0.05 hence we cannot reject the null hypothesis. So, as per Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test, the time series is non-stationary.

Check the stationarity of time series using KPSS test.

kpss.test(gas.ts)
## Warning in kpss.test(gas.ts): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  gas.ts
## KPSS Level = 7.7018, Truncation lag parameter = 5, p-value = 0.01

p-value = 0.01 < 0.05 hence we can reject the null hypothesis. So, as per KwiatkowskiPhillipsSchmidtShin Test, the time series is non-stationary.

Only stationary data can be used for ARIMA model. However, the data we have is non-stationary. So, lets try to check the transformation and differencing techniques in order to make the data stationary.

A stationary time series is one whose statistical properties such as mean, variance, autocorrelation, etc. are all constant over time. Let us plot and see by applying the techniques to make the data stationary.

#Plot the gas time series
plot(gas.ts)

#Plot log of gas time series
plot(log(gas.ts))

#Plot diff log of gas time series
plot(diff(log(gas.ts)))
abline(h=0)

In the plot of gas time series, we can see that the mean not constant over period of time. It is moving upward. Log of the time series is also like the same. Difference of log time series is showing stationarity. In this plot we can see that the mean is the same over period of time. So, applying diff (log()) on the gas time series makes the data stationary. Let us check this with ADF and KPSS tests.

Check the stationarity for diff log of time series using ADF test.

Null Hypothesis(H0): The series has a unit root. That means the time series is non-stationary. Alternate Hypothesis(H1): The series does not have a unit root. That means the time series is stationary.

adf.test(diff(log(gas.ts)))
## Warning in adf.test(diff(log(gas.ts))): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  diff(log(gas.ts))
## Dickey-Fuller = -17.55, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

p-value = 0.01 < 0.05 hence we can reject the null hypothesis. So, as per Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test, the diff log of time series is stationary.

Check the stationarity for diff log of time series using KPSS test.

Null Hypothesis(H0): The data is stationary. Alternate Hypothesis(H1): The data is non-stationary.

kpss.test(diff(log(gas.ts)))
## Warning in kpss.test(diff(log(gas.ts))): p-value greater than printed p-value
## 
##  KPSS Test for Level Stationarity
## 
## data:  diff(log(gas.ts))
## KPSS Level = 0.024909, Truncation lag parameter = 5, p-value = 0.1

p-value = 0.1 > 0.05 hence we cannot reject the null hypothesis. So, as per KwiatkowskiPhillipsSchmidtShin Test, the time series is stationary.
